GS, I\nINVESTMENT, f\nPROFITS,\nPROTECTION. I\nJ. S. SWORMSTEDT President X\nHENRY P. BLAIR Vice President\nALLEN C. CLARK Secretary X\n2\nGet the particulars from X\nX x\nA TiTi f hit a ir-^\\ n- atkt n?* n mm\nI wm. A. H,\nGeneral! Superintendent,\n603=605 F Street, I\nX J\nr hi\ni\nWARNER'S FIGHT FOR\nCONGRESS.\nGermantown, Md.\nI\nA large meeting was held last\ni night in this place. Col. Pearre's\nstatement that Mr. B. H. Warner\ni\nhas no brains is not indorsed by\ni\nthe crowd of people who heard\nhim speak for an hour last ntght.\n1\n_ __\nI i. I\nAddress on Peace and Arbitration. moria! Chape!, upon the campus of How?ni\nk*> ard University, tomorrow afternoon at\nPeace and Aroitration will be the _\nwo o. o clock. The meeting will be held\nsubject of an address by Secretary Straus umler thp au3piceg of the Mohonk naof\nthe Department of Commerce and La- tienal conference on peace. Music will\nbor before a mass meeting in Rankin Me- be furnished by a large chorus choir.\ni Hale's Honey i\nof Horehound Tar i\nReduces inflammation\nRemoves soreness\nj Tones the vocal cords\niil Clears the voice S\nHelps\nSpeakers and Singers\nAll Druggists Sell It\n5 Pike's Toothache Drops c\ncure In one minute. t\n<j\nr\nTALK ABOUT COLLEGE\ne\nMETHODISTS AT BOANOKE DIS- a\nCU'SS IMPORTANT MATTER.\ns\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nROANOKE. Va., March 28.?As indicated\nby The Star, the feature of yesterday's\nproceedings at the Baltimore conference\nwas the discussion of the ownership\nof Randolph-Macon College and its a\nacademies.\nAt 10 o'clock Rev. Dr. Sherman, chairman\nof the board of education, submitted\nthe report of the board. Dr. Sherman\nprefaced the report by saying his views v\nhad undergone a change. He now de- r\nsires the matter to stand as It is, giving t\nthe board pt trustees of the college the\nright of self-perpetuation, and not allow-\ning the conference the right of nominat- s\ning trustees. Dr. Sherman said that this\nwas practically the unanimous wish of I\nthe board of education. This would let\nthe property question remain as It has u\nbeen. c\nRev. Dr. Denny followed in a powerful v\nappeal to the conference to pass the res-\nolutions. which, if adopted, would stop 1\nthe college from benefiting by the Car- .r\nnegie provision. Dr. Denny showed that\nby the laws of Virginia church property\nwas not owned by denominations, as it\nought to be. and he wanted to protest and\nget some legal enactment which would\nnot \"shut churches out to the outer darkness\nof non-existence.\"\nA a A1 Tt 1\nuontena ior iae uoara. n\nJudge Newman and Judge Wood, mem- t\nbers of the board of trustees, followed in j1\nstrong speeches, contending that the t\nboard would see the denomination righted, t\nand that if the resolutions were passed S\nthey would reflect upon the integrity of J1\nthe trustees of the college.\nThe hour of adjournment stopped the b\ndiscussion, which will be continued today. p\nThe conference was invited by Dr. W.\nW. Smith to visit the Woman's College t\nat Lynchburg, and at 1 o'clock a special r\ntrain was placed at the disposal of the j\nministers. A large number went on the t\nexcursion. t\nRev. F. L. Day. professor in George\nWashington University, and Mr. W. W. s\nMillan of Washington are visitors at the s\nconference. 1\nSeveral important churches in the body v\nwill make unexpected changes, and big -r\nsurprises are in store in the appointments. T\nRev. Dr. J. R. Nelson addressed the\nconference Thursday night on the lmpor- t\ntance of Christianizing immigrants. He j\nshowed by an array of statistics that the\nchurch membership is not keeping pace\nwith foreign residents in this country, j\nHe recommended larger and more attractive\n\"downtown\" churches. In order\nto hold and influence foreign-born citizens.\nI\nThe classes for admission on trial and\nordination to deacon's orders were passed\nby the examining board.\nAbout was raised Thursday night\nfor improving mission property in japan.\nBishop Wilson paid his respects to Mark\nTwain and other critics of foreign missions\nby asserting that they did not know c\nwhat they were talking about. The bish- a\nop spoke for an hour on the theme of the a\nprogress and success of Christianity in _\nthe orient.\nc\nChinese Language Difficulties. a\nFrom tbe Contemporary Review.\nThe dialects or languages of the Chinese\nempire are very numerous and dissimilar.\nThus a Chinese speaking the\ndialect of the Kwangtung (Canton) province\nis not understood by a Chinese resld-\ning In the neighboring province of Fu- a\nkien The language or dialect spoken at b\nShanghai would be quite strange to the\npeople residing at Peking. P\nThe written characters of Chinese are, d\nhowever, understood and recognized by t\nsight throughout the whole empire in p\nthe same manner as our Arabic numerals, P\n1, 2. 3, 4, etc., are recognized by the eye\nthroughout Europe, but as these numerals b\nwhen pronounced or read, have entirely c\ndifferent sounds attached to them in\nEngland, France, Germany, Italy, etc.,\nso the Chinese written characters are c\nspoken in totally different words and s\nsounds in the several provinces of China, <with\nhowever, the imnortant excention c\nthat the Mandarin language la spoken 1\nor understood, more or less, throughout c\nthree-fourths of China, or. roughly speak- 11\nIng, in nearly all the provinces north and\nwest of the river Yangtze. c\nThe language known as Wen-li is the\nmedium by which the classical books of f\nChina have been handed down. It Is par\nexcellence the written language of China, c\nbut It is not generally understood by the E\ngreat mass of the people. The spoken c\nlanguage, viz.. Mandarin, may also be C\nwritten, and there Is a good deal of colloquial\nliterature in Mandarin. Versions J\nof the Bl'ble in the local patois have also f\nbeen produced in several districts of the J\nsoutheast, where the dialects are very I\nnumerous and diverse. t\nIn the Chinese written language there e\nare oer 40.nno distinct characters or symbols.\nand this vast number is being con- t\nstantly increased by the addition of new a\ncharacters to represent new scientific 1\nwords and .modern Ideas. I\nAlthough the Chinese are considered a\nliterary people and have naturally a desire\nfor education, yet. owing to the extreme\ndifficulty of mastering the Chinese n\ncharacters, it is estimated that only one a\nIn ten of the population can read or 1\nwrite. 1\no\nMeeting of American Mechanics.\nThe hall of Edward J. Ross Council, c\nao. jo, junior uraer uniiea American\nMechanics, was filled last Thursday even-\ning with Its members, together with the t\nmembers of other councils of the order\nof this and other Jurisdictions. After the T\nroutine business of the council had been\ntransacted a period of social enjoyment n\nfollowed, during which remarks on the E\ngrowth and prosperity of the order and\nkindred topics were made by Past State 0\nCouncilor S. A. Thompson of New Jersey\nand Past State Councilor S. Brashears,\nCouncilor G. T. Barksdale, Vice Councilor\nT n Tli i Hlav C2 1. Shnrou anH ntlmr 5\nW ?vuv??v v-?' V J \"tlltl\nmembers of Edward J. Ross Council, as\nwell as by Past State Councilor J. E.\nCrampton of Jasper Council. Past Councilor\nJ. T. Avery of Constella Council 11\nand Past Councilor J. W. Smallwood of \\n\nMount Vernon Council. The exercises D\nwere concluded with refreshments and a\n'smoker.\" r\nii\nI\nI\njjj The Sweetest s\nToasted Food a\nI IS CALLED I\n1 Post I I\n<W v t\n2\n11\nA vy/OAQJlWIVO^) ?ia\n3? *!<i\n\"The Taste Lingers.\" rc\nMade by Postum Cerea! Co., Limited, J\nBattle Creek, Michigan.\nr?\nV\nJELAY ON STATION TRACKS\nSB. SIMS BLAMES THE LOCAL\nBALL WAT COMPANIES.\nJays if They Would Consent to Be'gulation\nand Universal Transfers\nConferees Would Soon Agree.\nRepresentative Sims of Tennessee, one\n?f the House conferees on the Union staion\npermanent trackage bill, is decidedly\nllspleased with the little or no progress\nhat is being made by the conference com.\nnittee in reaching an agreement. In disussing\nthe matter today Mr. Sims hearti.\ny indorsed the idea?as-exemplified in the\nditoriat in The Star yesterday afternoon\n-of the newspapers of Washington doing\nill in their power to prod the conferees\nnto greater activity.\n\"The District committee of the House,\"\niait#Mr. Sims to a Star reporter, \"held\ntally sessions for several weeks while\nhis Union station permanent trackage\n(ill was in preparation, and finally secured\nhe passage of the measure by the House,\n\"onferees were then appointed, and alhough\nI am one of the three on the part\n(f the House, I do not mind stating that\nhp ITIPPtillUc r\\f t Itn onnforonoA oo?v?mil too\nnr> vi. iiiv; vnniviivc vvriitniliicc\ntre altogether too infrequent.\nHolds Railways Responsible.\n'\"One thing I am certain of?the conferes\ncould come to an agreement on the\n*nion station permanent trackage hill\nrlthin twenty minutes if the local street\nailway companies would only signify\nheir willingness to accept the universal\nransfer provision and the provision for\negulation by the District Commissioners\nr by the Interstate commerce commision.\n\"If the companies do not consider the\n\"Hstrlct Commissioners qualified or comletent\nto exercise the supervisory powers\nirovided by the bill, they certainly cannot\nirge the same objections to the interstate\nommerce commission, which has superisory\ncontrol of \"Jl'O.OOO miles of steam\nailwavs in the United States. I am sure,\noo. that the conferees, once the railway\nompanies would make known their willngness\nto accede to this proposition,\nrould be able to-settle their other and\nninor differences in a quarter of an\niour.\nIn the Event of Failure.\n\"If this hill is not passed at this session\nf Congress,\" continued Mr. Sims in the\nnost emphatic tone, \"and the tracks on\nhe Union station plaza are not built and\nI operation by the fourth of March next\no accommodate the great inauguration\nhrongs that will use the new station at\nhat time, then the people of the United\nItates will have a most illuminating obcct\nlesson of what the influence of street\nailway corporations in^he National oapial\nis able to accomplish in the way of\nlocking absolutely necessary legislation\nending in Congress.\n\"To my mind, there is no excuse for\nhe attitude of the street railway c?m anies\non this question. The great and\nnrreasing value and earning power of\nhe various lines under the two corporaIons\noperating here in Washington, and\nhe various other considerations involved,\nliould make them willing to accede to\nupervisory regulation?for that will com\"\n-and also he willing to accept the uni'ersal\ntransfer provision, which, in my\nipinion. in a comparatively short time\nvould prove to he hefe. as it has elsethere.\na help rather than a hindrance\no the financial betterment of all the\nines.\"\nMJSPICIOOS OPENING\nROTABLES COME OVER FROM\nBALTIMORE ON NEW LINE.\n'peolal Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE. Md.. March 'JS.?The spetal\ntrain\" of the Washington. Baltimore\nnd Annapolis Electric Railway having\nboard Mayor Mahool, former Mayor\n'imanus and about sixty city officials and\nouneHmen left the terminal station here\nt 11:30 this morning on an inspection\nrip. The first stop will be made at Acadmy\nJunction, where the shops will be inpeeted.\nand the trip resumed to Anapolis.\nAfter luncheon at Carvel Hall\nnd a trip over the city lines of the cornany\nthe party will proceed to Washingr>n.\nThe trip will conclude with a banquet\nt the New Willard. where the guests will\ne entertained by President Bishop.\nThose In the party are: Frank J. Mur1\ny, appeal tax court; J. Sewell Thomas,\nity register; George N. Numsen. presient\nsecond branch city council: Harry F.\nlooper. controller; Edward M. Parrish.\nresident of fire board: Dr. W. \\V. Cherry,\nresident first branch city council:\nVllliain W. Radcliffe, clerk first\nranch city council: E. H. Hargrave,\nommlttee clerk; J. H. Trautfelder. counilman:\nG. Heller, M.D., councilman; E.\nV. Klein, councilman: L. D. Green, counilman;\nJ. Betz. jr.. councilman: H. Jackon,\ncouncilman; I. Frank, councilman;\nI. White Ford, councilman; B. J. Lee,\nouncllman; A. E. Mullikin. councilman;\nr. O. Heatwole, councilman: S. J. West,\nouncilman; A. C. Binswager. courcilnan;\nH. A. Ulrich, councilman; R. D. Mc'urdy,\ncouncilman: F. T. Hellman, counilman:\nL. B. Etchison, councilman: H. L.\nirunfoi/i T n\nrv iciuciu, vuuui uillttii r*. iW.U.,\nouncilman: A. M. Sproesser, councilman;\nrV. Hlller, councilman: H. J. C. Hoffman,\nouncilman; J. D. Hushes, councilman;\nR. Downes. councilman; J. Davis, coun.\nilman; G. Warfleld, councilman, and Mr.\nJreen. councilman.\nEx-Councilmen F. W. Eckels, J. Davis,\nKronmiller, A. I. Wright. B. M. Watts,\nM. Dennle, G. Koiilsted. P. C. Kilmer,\nI. Hubert, E. C. I-ivingston and B. F.\nCelly and W. D. Marbury. council for\nhe Washington. Baltimore and Annapolis\nlectric railway.\nThe officials of the road who made the\nrip were President Bishop. Vice President\n.nd General Manager J. X. Shannahan.\n'raffic Manager W. K. Slaughter and\nMrertors George A. Craig and John G.\niasterton.\nThe Washington. Baltimore and Anapolls\nElectric Railway Company ran\nsocial excursion train over its road\noriay, leaving Baltimore at 11 o'clock\nhis morning. The present city officials\nf Baltimore, as well as many of those\nirho formerly conducted its municipal afairs,\nwere aboard as the guests of the\nompany, making a party of about sixty\nve. After a short stay at the ancient\nity of Annapolis, the party proceeded to\nhis city, arriving about 2:30 o'clock,\n.unclieon was served at the New \"Willard.\nThe return trip will he made at the\nonvenience of the tourists. Among those\nivited as guests were Mayor Mahool.\normer Mayor Timanus, present and forie\nmembers of the two brandies of the\nBaltimore city council and of the hoards\nf estimates and awards. The big new\nars of the company attracted attention.\nPROSECUTOR S JOKE.\nItartles Police Court Crowd With\nSmallpox Announcement.\nThe case of Enoch Washington, colored,\niving at 1120 ?r?th street southeast, who\nras arrested by tlie police of the lifth\nreclnct yesterday morning, charged with\nunning an unlicensed bar, was continued\n^definitely before Judge Mullowny of the\n'olice Court this morning at the instance\nf Assistant Corporation Counsel James\n'ugh.\n\"I ask for a continuance in the caso.\"\na.iri Mi*. I'ugn. at tne same time taking\nn uneasy look at the prisoner, \"because\n11 those in the crowd have smallpox.\"\nNo sooner was this announcement made\nhan several persons sitting near the\nrrisoner hastily moved their chairs, the\nlerk of the court sank back in his seat,\ntne or two prisoners in the dock began\ntrushing themselves nervously and there\nvas a general air of uneasiness in the\n:ourtroom.\n\"That is to say,\" continued Mr. Pugh.\neveral of our principal witnesses have\nmallpox. They live about a dozen blocks\niway from the defendant.\"\nMr. Pugh stated that the witnesses in\nluestion lived on Quander street and were\nemoved to the pesthouse by the health\nlepartment yesterday as suspects. I'pon\nlie assurance of Policeman Edwards of\nhe fifth precinct that he could have\nVashlngton in court when he was wanted\nhe latter was ieleased upou liis personal\necognizanca.\nA TP?\nH\ni pro\nf gre\nF s\nI V ?T\n1\nI A\ni* A ln8\nr r J\n4t I\n4> I .use\nr I\nI I Mi\nt do\nrafrs\nI\n-h i\nA I\n2 XiWKimNOW)MIWT.l 25th\nCLAIMS FOR DAMAGES\nBEFORE UNION STATION GRADE\nDAMAGE COMMISSION.\nThe Union station grade-damage commission.\ncomposed of Charles A. Baker,\nGeorge \\V. Moss and George Spransy, has\nconcluded its hearings in the matter of\nthe claims for damages filed by the owners\nof the real estate on the west side of\nNorth Capitol street between E and F\nstreets, in square and certain property\non the south side of Massachusetts\navenue, in square fill*!. The^commission\nwas occupied with the hearing of testimony\nand arguments in the case for\nabout three weeks.\nCounsel for the claimants contended that\nthe property mentioned has been damaged\nby the fill\" made ifi North Capitol street\n1 l- r\\i?\nam! in Massacnuseus avenue oy me i/mtriet\nCommissioners in connection with\ntlie establishment of the plaza in front ot\nthe new Union station, and urged the\ncommission to return appraisements in\nfavor of their clients. The property on\nNorth Capitol street is owned by the Anheuser-Buseh\nBrewing Company and by\nAlbert Carry, and about two-thirds of the\nproperty was purchased by the present\nowners after the \"fill\" was made in North\nCapitol street. The property in Massachusetts\navenue under consideration is\nowned by Mrs. Ella E. Steele.\nBenefits and Advantages.\nAttorneys Alexander H. Bell, Joseph A.\nBurkart, J. J. Darlington and Edwin Forrest\nappeared for the property owners,\nwhile A. Leftwich Sinclair, special attorney\nfor th<^ District, represented the government.\nAttorney Sinclair combatted the arguments\nof the claimants' counsel as to the\nproperty having been damaged by the\nchange of the grades of the streets and\nmaintained that while the improvements\non the land of the petitioners have been\npractically destroyed by the \"fill\" in question,\nthe benefits and advantages which\nhave resulted to the ground by reason of\nI the establishment of the Union station\nand the improvements incidental thereto\nare very great and more than compensate\nfor tMe value of the improvements and\nany other damage which may have been\nsuffered by the property owners. He accordingly\nasked the commission to return\nappraisements in favor of the government.\nIn appraising the damages alleged to\nhave resulted to property on account of\nchanges of street grades the commission\nis required by the act of Congress under\nwhich it was appointed to \"take into consideration\nany and ail benefits and advan.\ntages that may have accrued to such property\nby reason of the elimination of grade\ncrossings, the establishment of tlie Union\nrailroad station and terminals, and all\nworks, buildings and improvements authorized.\"\nIt is thought the commission will report\nits findings to the court within the next\nfew days.\nAged Citizens Dead.\nThe deaths of two venerable Washingtonians\nwere announced today. Matthew\nI'atton Ireland, aged eighty-two\nyears, died last evening at his home,\n11 Montello avenue northeast, and\ntlie funeral will take place at 4 o clock\ntomorrow afternoon. The remains will\nbe taken to Remington, Va., for interment.\nJohn K. Pfeil, aged eighty-three years,\ndied today at his home in West Washington.\nArrangements for the funeral\nare being made this afternoon.\nBuilding Permits Issued.\nInspector Ashford issued the following\nbuilding permits today:\nTo William Murphy, one two-story\nbrick dwelling at 1310 East Capitol street\nestimated to cost ?l),000; architect, E.\nWebb; builder, William Murphy.\nTo J. B. Bowling, one two-story frame\ndwelling at 4-15 Iowa avenue northwest,\nestimated to cost $4,000; architect, A. H.\nBeers; builder. M. H. Bray.\nELECT?\nSfin frorfn[kin\n-=i .V.\nFORTY YEARS\nIN HOUSEHOLD USE.\nUNEQUALLED\nFOR CLEANING AND POLISHING\nSILVERWARE\nAND ALL FINE METALS.\nSend address for a FREE SAMPLE,\nTHE ELECTRO SILICON CO..\n30 Cliff St.. New York.\nGROCERS AND DRUGGISTS SELL IS.\nCl2-u.2Gt.28\nr?\nTTTfTTTTTTTTTTTTT\nrosidoiit I\nDnce expressed his views\nhiBition as follows: \"Pro\nat injury to the cause of\npecies of intemperance w\n:s beyond the bounds of\nrnipts to control a man's\nThe more enlightened\niperance promoters realiz\niragement of the PROF\nthe surest success of the\nRich in malt and hop exti\nbut an infinitesimal perb\n777 n 9\nHeuncli s\nare beverages which EV\nwith PROFIT. They a\nst hygienically appointed\nd?cooled in filtered air, c\ns?bottled through hermet\nthen pasteurized. Moder\n\\ERZEN, SENATE a\nyou and your family last\ndoz. Maerzen Bottled at\nenateT$I.75. The Brewer>\nottle rebate, 50c. For ffiOBTBe U?<\n/hr. Heurich Br^\n26th, D and Water Sts.\nIN THE LABOR WORLD\nTo\nr\nBIG REDUCTION IN WORKING of\nFORCE BY NEW HAVEN. ,n\nthi\na\nNEW HAVEN. Cofnn., March 28.-By \\th;\nthe laying' off of 105 men today at the\nst r\nSpring street shops of the New York.\nNew Haven and Hartford railroad the ?jt\nworking force was reduced to about un\ntwenty-five, as against about 800 when the to\nshops are running full-handed. There\nwas some talk last night that if the rjv\ncompany should put into force the piece- to\nwork rule today the men who are now\nemployed at the shops would hold them- we\nselves in readiness to obey a strike order.\nIt was first proposed that the piece-work\nrule should be inaugurated March 10,\nbut a conference between representatives ipj\nof the company and of its employes resulted\nin postponing any action 'until\nMarch 28. It was also reported here that p?,\nth 3 steamer Puritan, which is now at\nNew York, was being put in readiness 1\nto be brought to this city to serve as ne!\nquarters ror new men. in case any iruu- ?i.\nble on the railroad developed. tot\nExeter Cotton Mills Cut Wages. Be\nEXETER. X. H.. March 28.?Notices of T'r\na 10 per cent reduction in wages, to take ,or\neffect next Monday, were posted at the )n\ncotton mills of the Exeter Manufacturing:\nCompany yesterday. About -100 operatives\nare affected. All\nWages of 500 Millbands Cut.\nWARREN. R. I.. March 28?Notices on\nwere posted in the Parker Mills here\niflc\nyesterday announcing a reduction of 10\nper cent in* wages, to take effect April 6. jjrj\nThe mill employs nearly 500 hands. to\nDye and Extract Mill to Close. a\nSTAMFORD, Conn., March 28.?The riv\nmills of the Stamford Manufacturing r'v\nCompany will close today for an indeflnit3\nperiod, enforcing idleness upon about ac)\n200 men. The company supplies dyes and ch<\nextracts. wit\nQuarrying Affected by Strike. piv\nBARRE, Vt., March 28.?That the Barre pie\ngranite owners have given up hopes of an\nearly settlement of the strike which has tlie\nkept their quarries practically closed dur- chi\ning the past month seems to be indicated scr\nby the decision of several to stop the ine\npumps in the quarries. The continuance\nof the strike has resulted in an exodus ,m\nof foreigners from this city and other )lj\nquarrying centers affected by the strike. i4J\nof\nVI. ...1 Til A 1\nMustis xiueis rinu tor oiriKf. cus\nLEAVENWORTH. Kan., March 2*.Miners\nhere are preparing for the coming |ca\nstrike of the coal miners. All of the\nmine mules are being offered for sale,\napparently In anticipation of a long con- S!\ntest. A large supply of coal has already\nbeen stored by the railroads. In Leavenworth\n1/100 men will be affected.\nPITTSBURG, Kan.. March 28.-On Tues- 1\nday next all of the coal mines in this\ndistrict will shut down by mutual con- cei\nsent of the miners and operators, and lar\nwill remain closed for sixty days.'- The P*1\ncontract between the miners and the ter\nmine owners expires Tuesday, and until jng\nnegotiations are completed for the new\ncontract the mines will remain closed.\nBig Order for Equipment.\nPHILADELPHIA, March 28. Antici- C\npatlng the early return of prosperity, and V\nto be prepared for a largely increased\nbusiness with the New England ma/kets,\nan order for $500,000 worth of equipment\nwill be placed by the ?ehigli and^ NewEngland\nRailroad Company within the\nnext few days. The order calling for 250\ncuai ana ireigni cars ana inree locomotives\nis the largest ever placed by this\nroad, its equipment heretofore having\nbeen limited to less than SOU cars.\nRailway Prosperity Returning.\nCHICAGO. March ii8.?Railroad officials\nip charge of operation have received some\nencouragement within the last week. Executives\nin Chicago declare that after sev- 7\neral months the roads are beginning to rib\n\"see the light\" of Improved conditions and an<\na return of railroad prosp